  <sect1 id="usage">
    <title>Using the GNU Build Tools</title>

    <para>

      This section of the document introduces various GNU build tools
      and explains how to use them.  Though the treatment would not be in
      depth, it should help you understand the files that these tools
      operate on.  After going though this section of the HOWTO, you
      would be able to read the documents provided here as references
      and experiment with the features that these tools have to offer.

    </para>

    <sect2 id="make-use">
      <title>GNU Make</title>

      <para>

        If you are reading this document, it is possible that you
        already have prior experience with the Make tool.  However, any
        discussion of the GNU build system and tools would be incomplete
        without a mention of Make.

      </para>

      <sect3 id="make-whatis">
        <title>What is Make</title>

        <para>
        
          Make is a utility for automatic compilation of programs.  It is
          usually used in projects to find out if the files that a
          certain <quote>target</quote> depends on have changed and
          re-generates the target.

        </para>
      </sect3>

      <sect3 id="make-example">
        <title>Make in action</title>

        <para>

          A very minimal <filename>Makefile</filename> would look like:

        </para>

<programlisting>
$ cat Makefile

foo: foo.c
         gcc -o foo foo.c
</programlisting>

        <para>

          The target in this <filename>Makefile</filename> is
          <filename>foo</filename> and it depends on the
          <filename>foo.c</filename> dependancy.  The second line tells
          make how to build the target in case the dependancy changes.

        </para>

        <para>

          A slightly more useful example would be:

        </para>

<programlisting>
$ cat Makefile

default: hw

hw: hello.o world.o
        gcc -o hw hello.o world.o -lm

hello.o: hello.c hello.h
        gcc -c hello.c

world.o: world.c world.h
        gcc -c world.c

clean:
        rm -f hw hello.o world.o
</programlisting>

        <para>

          The target in this <filename>Makefile</filename> (which is the
          first target that appears in the
          <filename>Makefile</filename>) is <literal>default</literal>.
          <literal>default</literal> depends on <literal>hw</literal>
          which inturn depends on <filename>hello.o</filename> and
          <filename>world.o</filename>.  These can be `made' using the
          rules that have been specified for them.  For example,
          <filename>hello.o</filename> is created using the command
          <command>gcc -c hello.c</command> whenever
          <filename>hello.c</filename> or <filename>hello.h</filename>
          are modified.

        </para>

        <para>

          The other target <literal>clean</literal> can be invoked
          explicitly to remove the target files that have been
          generated.

        </para>

<programlisting>
$ make clean
rm -f hw hello.o world.o
</programlisting>

        <para>

          <filename>Makefiles</filename> can also be written using
          variables and wild-cards making them easy to modify.  For
          example, the above <filename>Makefile</filename> could be
          re-written as:

        </para>

<programlisting>
$ cat Makefile

TARGET = hw
OBJS = hello.o world.o
CC = gcc
CCOPTS = -c
LOPTS = -lm

all: $(TARGET)

$(TARGET): $(OBJS)
        $(CC) -o $@ $(OBJS) $(LOPTS)

%.o: %.c %.h
        $(CC) $(CCOPTS) $<

clean:
        rm -rf $(TARGET) $(OBJS)
</programlisting>

        <para>

          Every <literal>$(VARIABLE)</literal> in the
          <filename>Makefile</filename> is replaced with its value.  The
          generic rule <literal>%.o: %.c %.h</literal> <footnote> <para>
          In general, one source file would depend on more than one
          header file and the dependency rule is not as simple as this.
          It is infact difficult to keep track of dependencies on header
          files and their dependencies with nested includes.  There are
          ways of handling this (see the manual page of makedepend on
          your Linux machine and the -M option to gcc), but using
          automake makes this a cakewalk.  </para> </footnote> says that
          each <filename>.o</filename> file is dependant on the
          corresponding <filename>.c</filename> and the
          <filename>.h</filename> files.  <literal>$@</literal> refers to
          the current target and <literal>$&lt</literal> refers to the
          first one among the list of dependencies of the current
          target.  Note that this version of the
          <filename>Makefile</filename> does not need a lot of
          modifications if a single source file and the corresponding
          header files are added.

        </para>

        <para>

          GNU Make has several other interesting features like the VPATH
          directive to locate the source files that are not co-located
          with the <filename>Makefile</filename>, facility for
          sophisticated wildcards etc.  These can be found from the
          <citetitle>official GNU Make manual</citetitle> in <xref
          linkend=resources>.

        </para>

      </sect3>

      <sect3 id="make-gnumakefile">
        <title>A GNU <filename>Makefile</filename></title>

        <para>

          <filename>Makefile</filename>s that go with software packages
          that follow the GNU <filename>Makefile</filename> conventions
          have a few standard targets that provide useful and commonly
          used functionality like:

        </para>

        <itemizedlist>
          <listitem>
            <para>
              all: to build the package
            </para>
          </listitem>

          <listitem>
            <para>
              clean: which removes all the generated files
            </para>
          </listitem>

          <listitem>
            <para>
              tags: generates the TAGS file for source browsing
            </para>
          </listitem>

          <listitem>
            <para>

              check: which executes any automated test cases that have
              been included with the package.

            </para>
          </listitem>

          <listitem>
            <para>

              dist: creates a .tar.gz distribution of the software package.

            </para>
          </listitem>

          <listitem>
            <para>

              uninstall: removes the files that have been installed

            </para>
          </listitem>
        </itemizedlist>

        <para>

          and many more ...

        </para>

        <para>

          Writing the dependencies and rules for these targets is a
          non-trivial task and involves some effort.  Automake solves
          this problem by generating all the standard targets.

        </para>
      </sect3>

    </sect2>

